          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>STCW Basic Safety + ENG1 + RYA Powerboat L2 (deck) or Food Hygiene (interior)</li>
            <li>$26K&ndash;$40K base, plus $5K&ndash;$15K charter tips</li>
            <li>First-time-buyer FHA 3.5% down realistic after 2-year history</li>
            <li>South Florida starter condo or townhouse, $250K&ndash;$400K target</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See entry-level qualification mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Deckhand / Stewardess (1&ndash;3 seasons)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Second or third season. Charter-active. Tips are real now."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Same credentials, plus EDH (Efficient Deck Hand) or Crowd &amp; Crisis Mgmt</li>
            <li>$30K&ndash;$50K base, plus $15K&ndash;$40K charter tips</li>
            <li>Conventional 5% down with two-year W-2 + declared tip history</li>
            <li>$300K&ndash;$550K South Florida purchase common</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See mid-tier crew qualification mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Bosun / 2nd Stew (3&ndash;6 seasons)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Line manager tier. Running a department under the Chief or Captain."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Plus PDSD (security) and supervisor-level role credentials</li>
            <li>$43K&ndash;$76K base, plus $20K&ndash;$50K charter tips</li>
            <li>Conventional with charter-bonus included as variable income</li>
            <li>$400K&ndash;$700K South Florida purchase, often with co-borrower partner</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See bosun &amp; 2nd stew mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Chief Stew / Yacht Chef</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Department head. Senior interior or galley role on a 50m+."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Chief Stew: GUEST certification; Chef: Food Hygiene L3, culinary credentials</li>
            <li>$78K&ndash;$156K base, plus $30K&ndash;$80K charter tips</li>
            <li>Conventional, jumbo, or Non-QM bank-statement for FEIE-heavy years</li>
            <li>$600K&ndash;$1.1M South Florida purchase, often with rental property</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See senior crew mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Specialty: ETO / Purser / Dive Instructor</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Specialized skill role &mdash; electrical, finance, watersports."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Role-specific credentials (electrical engineering, PADI/IDC, purser cert)</li>
            <li>$60K&ndash;$120K base plus specialty premium and charter tips</li>
            <li>Conventional with documented specialty pay premium</li>
            <li>$450K&ndash;$850K South Florida purchase common</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See specialty role mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your yacht crew mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every yacht crew file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on whether your W-2 is U.S.-issued, foreign-flagged, charter-tip-heavy, or supplemented with day-work or land-based seasonal income.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; U.S.-flagged W-2 with charter tip averaging</h3>
      <p>The cleanest case at the entry tier. You work on a U.S.-flagged charter yacht (common in South Florida and the Bahamas), receive a W-2 from a U.S. payroll, and declare tips either on the W-2 (Box 7 allocated tips) or on Form 4137. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae Selling Guide B3-3.1-01</a>, declared tip income with a two-year history qualifies as variable income on the average. The W-2 base plus the declared tip line combined produce the qualifying income. For first-time crew home-buyers, this is the dominant qualifying path.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; Foreign-flagged W-2 with FEIE handling</h3>
      <p>Common for crew on superyachts above 30m, where roughly 70% of vessels are foreign-flagged. The Cayman Islands, Marshall Islands, Malta, or Isle of Man management company issues a W-2-equivalent statement. U.S.-citizen crew report this on the 1040 and may claim the <a href="https://www.irs.gov/individuals/international-taxpayers/foreign-earned-income-exclusion" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Foreign Earned Income Exclusion (Form 2555)</a>, currently $126,500 for 2024. The exclusion reduces taxable income but the gross wages still appear on Form 2555 line 19 &mdash; that gross plus the declared tips is the qualifying number we use, not the post-exclusion AGI.</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; Bank-statement (Non-QM) for tip-heavy crew</h3>
      <p>When the crew member&rsquo;s pay is heavily tip-weighted (charter chef and chief stew on hot charter vessels), when tips arrive in cash and are slow to declare, or when pay moves across multiple vessels during a season, Non-QM bank-statement underwriting is the practical path. <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/43/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CFPB Reg Z&rsquo;s Ability-to-Repay rule</a> permits non-QM lending with compensating factors. We qualify on 12 or 24 months of personal bank deposits with an expense-ratio adjustment. For yacht crew this often beats the W-2 + AGI path because the deposit pattern shows the full take-home including tips that may not be perfectly declared.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; Cross-season income smoothing (W-2 + 1099 + day-work)</h3>
      <p>Some crew supplement primary contract income with off-season day work (yacht detailing, freelance chef catering, marine-services consulting). This generates a mix of W-2 and 1099 income across a year. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae Selling Guide B3-3.3-02</a>, mixed income qualifies once a two-year history exists. We total the gross from all sources and verify the recurring pattern. This is also the dominant method for crew transitioning out of yachting into a marine-trades land career.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/1295138/pexels-photo-1295138.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on a yacht crew file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income components that show up consistently on yacht crew files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore or mis-categorize. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to know what to ask for.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Charter tip pool share</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">For yacht crew, tip income is often 40&ndash;100% of base salary &mdash; not a bonus, the primary income mechanism. Industry standard is 10&ndash;15% of charter fee distributed among crew. On a 50m vessel chartering 12 weeks at $200K/week, the crew pool is $240K&ndash;$360K split across 8&ndash;12 crew. <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/tip-recordkeeping-and-reporting" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">IRS tip-reporting rules</a> require declaration on Form 4137 or as W-2 wages. With two years of declared history, this qualifies as variable income.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Longevity / season-completion bonus</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Many vessels pay a season-completion bonus &mdash; commonly equal to one month&rsquo;s base &mdash; for crew who finish the contract season without quitting. The bonus shows on the W-2 as additional wages. <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a> permits including this in qualifying income with two-year history. Generalist lenders ignore it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Room-and-board value not on the W-2</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Yacht crew live aboard. Food, housing, laundry, and travel during the season are covered. This is functionally a $20K&ndash;$40K/year living-expense subsidy that doesn&rsquo;t appear on any tax form. It doesn&rsquo;t add to qualifying income directly, but it dramatically lowers DTI capacity calculations &mdash; we document the live-aboard pattern so underwriters understand why a crew member with $50K of declared W-2 has saved $80K in two years.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Foreign Earned Income Exclusion</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">U.S.-citizen crew on foreign-flagged vessels who spent 330+ days outside the U.S. claim the <a href="https://www.irs.gov/individuals/international-taxpayers/foreign-earned-income-exclusion" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">FEIE</a> on Form 2555. For crew this often eliminates federal income tax entirely on $60K&ndash;$120K gross. Generalist lenders see the near-zero AGI and decline. We use the gross wages from Form 2555 line 19 plus declared tips as qualifying income, not the post-exclusion AGI.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Specialty pay premiums (ETO, dive, language)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Crew with specialty skills &mdash; ETO with electrical engineering credentials, PADI Divemaster, fluent in a guest-relevant language, certified yoga instructor, masseuse &mdash; command pay premiums of 10&ndash;25% over the same role without the specialty. The premium shows on the W-2 but generalist lenders read it as base salary and miss the trend if the crew member just earned the specialty.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">F</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Off-season day-work income</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Crew often supplement contract income with day work between seasons &mdash; yacht detailing, freelance chef catering, marine-trades work in Fort Lauderdale. This produces 1099 income on Schedule C that the crew member often forgets to mention until underwriting. With two-year Schedule C history, the off-season income aggregates with the W-2 base under self-employed income rules.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #5: LOAN PROGRAM MATRIX ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">05 &middot; Match the program to the crew tier</div>
        <h2>Which loan program fits your yacht crew mortgage situation.</h2>
        <p>Seven loan-program categories cover essentially every yacht crew purchase or refinance we&rsquo;ve closed. Each has a clear best-fit crew tier.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="loan-program-grid">

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">FHA</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Entry-tier crew building first two-year W-2 + tip history</li>
            <li>3.5% down with credit score 580+</li>
            <li>Loan limits up to $498,257 (FL low-cost area) for 2024</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Junior deckhand &amp; stew first home</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Conventional (Fannie / Freddie)</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>2nd&ndash;3rd-season crew with stable W-2 + declared tips</li>
            <li>5&ndash;20% down, no PMI above 20%</li>
            <li>Loan limits up to $766,550 (FL conforming) for 2024-25</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Deckhand &amp; stew with tip history</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">VA Loan</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Crew with U.S. military service (Navy, USCG common transition)</li>
            <li>0% down, no PMI, competitive rates</li>
            <li>No loan limit for fully-entitled veterans</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Navy/USCG transition crew</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Jumbo</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Senior crew (Chief Stew, Yacht Chef) on 50m+ vessels</li>
            <li>10&ndash;20% down typical</li>
            <li>Rate within 0.25% of conforming for clean files</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Chief Stew &amp; Yacht Chef tier</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Non-QM Bank-Statement</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Tip-heavy crew with FEIE-reduced or low AGI</li>
            <li>12 or 24 months of personal deposits at 50&ndash;75% counting</li>
            <li>Rate 0.5&ndash;1.0% higher than conforming</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Tip-heavy foreign-flagged crew</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">1099-Only / Asset-Depletion</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Transitioning crew with mixed W-2/1099 income</li>
            <li>Asset-depletion for crew with $300K+ liquid reserves</li>
            <li>Specialty Non-QM lenders</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Crew exiting to land career</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">USDA Rural / Down-Payment Assistance</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Crew buying outside the immediate FtL/Miami metro</li>
            <li>0% down USDA in eligible rural Florida areas</li>
            <li>Florida HFA Hometown Heroes for eligible occupations</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Lower-cost-market FTB crew</div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #6: INDUSTRY CONTEXT ============ -->
  <section class="section section-tinted">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">06 &middot; Why this mortgage is harder than it should be</div>
        <h2>The yacht crew mortgage in context: 6 forces shaping how crew qualify.</h2>
        <p>The reason a generalist lender struggles with a yacht crew file isn&rsquo;t laziness. It&rsquo;s that yacht crew employment combines multiple unusual features &mdash; live-aboard housing, charter tip income larger than base wage, foreign-flagged W-2, dual-jurisdiction tax filing, short career windows &mdash; that don&rsquo;t map onto standard land-based W-2 underwriting.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Force 1 &mdash; STCW Basic Safety + ENG1 universal entry</h3>
      <p>All commercial yacht crew must hold two credentials before joining a vessel: the <a href="https://www.imo.org/en/OurWork/HumanElement/Pages/STCW-Convention.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">STCW</a> Basic Safety Training certificate (a 5-day course covering personal survival, fire fighting, first aid, personal safety) and the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/maritime-and-coastguard-agency" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">UK MCA ENG1 medical certificate</a> (or an accepted equivalent). Together they cost $1,200&ndash;$1,800 and are the entry gate to every commercial yacht crew role globally.</p>

      <h3>Force 2 &mdash; Charter tip income as primary, not bonus</h3>
      <p>Unlike most service-industry tip work, yacht crew tip income often equals or exceeds base salary. The crew pool is 10&ndash;15% of charter revenue, distributed by tip share among crew based on seniority. For deckhands and stews on hot charter vessels, this means the W-2 base understates take-home by 50&ndash;100%. The implication: any lender that ignores declared tip income misjudges the file by half.</p>

      <h3>Force 3 &mdash; Live-aboard housing as hidden compensation</h3>
      <p>While at sea, crew pay zero living expenses &mdash; food, lodging, utilities, and uniforms are vessel-provided. This is not taxable income (it&rsquo;s exempt under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/119" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">26 USC &sect; 119</a> as condition-of-employment lodging), but it dramatically increases savings rate. A deckhand earning $40K W-2 + $15K tips often saves $30K&ndash;$40K/year &mdash; a fact underwriters need help recognizing.</p>

      <h3>Force 4 &mdash; Foreign vessel registry economics</h3>
      <p>Approximately 70% of yachts above 30 meters are foreign-flagged (Cayman, Marshall Islands, Malta, Isle of Man, Bermuda) for tax and regulatory reasons. Even U.S.-resident crew often receive wages from a foreign-domiciled management company. Compliance with U.S. tax filing remains the crew&rsquo;s responsibility via <a href="https://www.irs.gov/individuals/international-taxpayers/foreign-earned-income-exclusion" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FEIE on Form 2555</a> and <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/comparison-of-form-8938-and-fbar-requirements" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FBAR/Form 8938</a> filings.</p>

      <h3>Force 5 &mdash; South Florida market concentration</h3>
      <p>Fort Lauderdale is the U.S. center of yacht crew employment, with the largest concentration of MCA- and USCG-approved training schools, the densest marina infrastructure for vessels in the 30&ndash;100m range, and easy access to Caribbean charter season. Approximately 60% of our yacht crew mortgages are on South Florida properties &mdash; commonly Pompano Beach, Wilton Manors, Coral Springs, and Davie.</p>

      <h3>Force 6 &mdash; The 5-to-7-year career window</h3>
      <p>Unlike captain or engineer careers that span 20+ years, most yacht crew careers run 3&ndash;7 years before transitioning to land &mdash; either by promotion to captain/engineer/officer tracks, or by exit to marine-trades land careers (yacht broker, charter manager, marina ops, marine retail). The mortgage purchase typically happens at year 4&ndash;6, funded by accumulated rotation savings and timed before the income transition.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

