  <!-- ============ H2 #9: 25-FAQ SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto var(--s-8);">
        <div class="eyebrow">09 &middot; Yacht crew mortgage FAQs</div>
        <h2>Yacht crew mortgage questions, answered.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">

        <div class="faq-cross-links" style="margin-bottom: var(--s-10); padding: var(--s-6); background: var(--paper-warm); border-left: 3px solid var(--blue);">
          <p style="margin: 0 0 var(--s-3) 0; font-family: var(--serif); font-size: var(--text-md); font-weight: 500;">More <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/yacht-professionals/" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">yacht crew mortgage</a> resources at Stairway</p>
          <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: var(--s-5); font-size: var(--text-sm); line-height: 1.7; list-style: none;">
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/yacht-professionals/">All yacht professional mortgage programs</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/fha-loan/">FHA loan for first-time-buyer crew</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/conventional-loan/">Conventional yacht crew mortgage details</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/va-loan/">VA loan for Navy/USCG transition crew</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/bank-statement-loan/">Bank-statement loan for tip-heavy crew</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/1099-loan/">1099 loan for crew with side day-work</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/first-time-home-buyer/">First-time home buyer programs &amp; assistance</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/purchase-inquiry/">Start your yacht crew mortgage pre-approval</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can a yacht crew member with only one year of W-2 history qualify for a mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, in specific paths. FHA allows qualification with 12 months of W-2 history if the income is stable and the credit profile is clean. Conventional Fannie Mae requires two years of variable-income history but accepts one year if your prior employment was in a related role. For most crew the cleanest path is to wait until you have two seasons of W-2 + declared tip history.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I include charter tip income in my qualifying income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, with declared-tip documentation. <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/tip-recordkeeping-and-reporting" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRS tip-reporting rules</a> require declared tips on Form 4137 (if not allocated by employer) or as W-2 wages (if allocated). With two years of declared tip history, the average qualifies as variable income alongside the W-2 base. Undeclared tips can&rsquo;t be used. This is the single most important documentation discipline for yacht crew mortgages.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My W-2 comes from a Cayman or Marshall Islands management company. Will lenders accept it?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, with the right lender. Foreign-issued W-2s are accepted under both conventional and Non-QM programs as long as the income is documented through the underlying SEA, the management company can verify employment, and the crew member&rsquo;s U.S. tax filings reconcile. Cayman, Marshall Islands, Malta, Isle of Man, and Bermuda are all common; we&rsquo;ve closed loans with crew paid from each.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">04</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Does the value of room-and-board onboard count as income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No. Under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/119" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">26 USC &sect; 119</a>, lodging and meals furnished by an employer as a condition of employment (which applies to yacht crew) are excluded from taxable income. It doesn&rsquo;t add to qualifying income but it dramatically increases your savings capacity, which we document to help underwriters understand why your reserves are larger than the W-2 might suggest.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">05</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the Foreign Earned Income Exclusion affect my mortgage qualification?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">FEIE reduces your taxable income on Form 1040 line 8 but doesn&rsquo;t reduce the gross wages on your W-2 or Form 2555 line 19. Generalist lenders look at the AGI and decline. We use the gross wages from line 19 plus declared tips as the qualifying income. For a crew member earning $80K gross who excluded the full $80K under FEIE, the qualifying income is $80K &mdash; not $0.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Do FBAR and FinCEN 114 filings affect my mortgage approval?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Not directly. The filings are informational. But they signal a multi-jurisdiction tax picture, and an underwriter unfamiliar with maritime files may incorrectly treat the foreign accounts as undisclosed. We document foreign-account holdings up front so there are no surprises.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How is rotational pay treated for qualifying income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>, variable income with a two-year history is averaged across the period. Rotation isn&rsquo;t treated as instability &mdash; it&rsquo;s a known pattern. We document the rotation schedule via the SEA and use the annual W-2 totals plus declared tips as the average.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Should I declare all my tips even if no one&rsquo;s checking?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For mortgage purposes, yes &mdash; aggressively. Undeclared cash tips are invisible to underwriting and reduce your qualifying income dollar-for-dollar. A crew member who declares $30K in tips can qualify for $150K&ndash;$200K more mortgage than one who doesn&rsquo;t. The marginal tax cost of declaring (often offset by FEIE entirely) is small compared to the mortgage capacity gain. Consult your CPA about Form 4137.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I have Navy or Coast Guard service. Does that help?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Significantly. Veterans qualify for VA loans with 0% down and no PMI, often saving $300&ndash;$500/month versus FHA financing. Many Navy and USCG transition crew use their service for both the maritime career path and the VA loan benefit. We document service through the DD-214 and Certificate of Eligibility.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What if I work for multiple vessels in one year?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Common pattern &mdash; a crew member finishes one season and starts another on a different vessel. The two W-2s aggregate cleanly if both are in the same role tier (e.g., deckhand to deckhand). If one is a promotion (deckhand to bosun), we&rsquo;d use the trailing-12 from the higher-tier position once a 60&ndash;90-day pay history is established.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use my rotation savings as a down payment without seasoning?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, with documentation of source. Lenders require 60&ndash;90 days of "seasoning" for down-payment funds. Rotation savings that have been accumulating for seasons pass seasoning trivially. New large deposits (e.g., a $15K end-of-season tip distribution) require explanation &mdash; we document the source as charter tip pool with the season&rsquo;s tip statement.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Do I need to be in the U.S. when I apply for a mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No. Closing remotely is standard for yacht-crew mortgages &mdash; many of our clients close from a marina in the Med or Caribbean. Mobile notary, e-signature where state law permits, and FedEx&rsquo;d documents all work. We coordinate timing around your rotation schedule.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How much do I really need for a down payment as yacht crew?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Depends on the program. FHA: 3.5%. Conventional: 5% with PMI, 20% without. VA: 0%. Jumbo: typically 10&ndash;20%. USDA in rural eligible areas: 0%. Many crew can afford 10&ndash;20% down because of low living expenses while at sea &mdash; though FHA 3.5% may make sense to preserve cash reserves.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Does Florida Hometown Heroes apply to yacht crew?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Generally no &mdash; the program is designed for first-responders, teachers, healthcare workers, and similar publicly-defined service occupations. But some crew are eligible if they hold a secondary qualifying occupation (e.g., a former teacher now working as crew). We check eligibility at the start of every file.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My SEA pays in euros. How is the currency conversion handled?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For U.S. tax purposes, the IRS publishes annual average exchange rates that apply to Form 2555 and the 1040. The same rates carry into mortgage qualification &mdash; the lender converts the foreign-currency wages to USD using the IRS rate for the year. For trailing-12-month income, we use a blended rate based on actual pay periods.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I qualify while I&rsquo;m off-rotation or between vessels?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes. Off-rotation is part of the yacht-crew employment structure, not unemployment. The W-2 reports total annual wages including off-rotation periods. Lenders qualify on the annualized number. A gap of 30&ndash;90 days between contracts is normal and doesn&rsquo;t affect qualification.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Does training cost (STCW + ENG1) factor into qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Indirectly. Training costs aren&rsquo;t debt unless financed; if paid in cash, they reduce reserves. If your vessel reimbursed training, that&rsquo;s included in the W-2 and we exclude it from recurring-income calculations.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I buy a primary residence and a rental property simultaneously?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, if reserves and DTI permit. Some senior crew use rotation savings for both. The rental property qualifies under DSCR (Debt Service Coverage Ratio) Non-QM rules, which don&rsquo;t affect personal DTI. This is common for chief-stew-tier crew planning their land transition.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What happens if my ENG1 medical fails on renewal?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">ENG1 fitness affects employability &mdash; the mortgage doesn&rsquo;t care about the credential per se. If an ENG1 failure causes a pay drop or career change, that&rsquo;s a material change that affects future refinancing but not an existing mortgage. We help time refinance applications around credential renewal cycles.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically for yacht crew?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No dedicated "yacht crew" mortgage program exists. But FHA, conventional, VA, Non-QM bank-statement, and 1099 programs all accept yacht crew files when documented correctly. The specialty is in the broker who reads the SEA and the tip ledger.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My partner is also yacht crew. Can we combine incomes?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes. Co-borrower files combine W-2s, bonuses, and declared tip income from both partners. Crew-plus-crew households are common and combined incomes routinely support $500K+ purchases at the deckhand+stew tier and $1M+ at the bosun+chief-stew tier.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What happens to my mortgage when I exit yachting?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Nothing directly. The mortgage doesn&rsquo;t change. But your future refinancing capacity depends on the land-career income that follows. We help crew time their first mortgage purchase to maximize qualifying income before any career transition that might reduce W-2 levels.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Should I buy before or after I exit yachting?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Almost always before. Crew income with declared tips is often higher than the first land-career income in the related fields (yacht brokerage, marina ops, marine retail). Qualifying while your yacht-tip W-2 is at peak gives you the largest mortgage. We model both scenarios in the consult.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What loan amount can I qualify for at $80K of yacht crew income (base + tips)?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Rough estimate: at 43% DTI and current rates, $80K gross income supports a total monthly housing payment of roughly $2,850 (less if you have other debts). That maps to a $300K&ndash;$400K mortgage depending on rate, taxes, insurance, and PMI. We model your specific scenario in the 20-minute consult.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 30&ndash;60 days before you intend to make an offer. Yacht crew files take longer to underwrite than W-2 desk-job files because of the foreign-flagged pay, tip declaration, and FEIE documentation requirements. Starting early prevents close-of-escrow surprises. We can run a soft pre-approval before you&rsquo;re even house-hunting.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

